              <h2>How to use this interactive periodic table</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed to give you the speed of a classroom wall
                chart with the depth of a reference handbook. Click any element
                to see its key properties, or use the search and filters to
                focus on what you need.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Search bar:</strong> type a <em>name</em> (“oxygen”),
                  <em>symbol</em> (“O”), or <em>atomic number</em> (“8”).
                  Matching elements are highlighted and others are dimmed.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Color by property:</strong> switch between coloring by
                  category, state at room temperature, electronegativity, atomic
                  mass, or atomic radius to visualize periodic trends.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Quick filters:</strong> instantly show only nonmetals,
                  noble gases, alkali metals, alkaline earth metals, or
                  transition metals.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Detail panel:</strong> shows atomic number, standard
                  atomic weight, period/group, block, density, melting/boiling
                  point, electronegativity, radius, oxidation states, and
                  electron configuration.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Key periodic trends you can explore</h2>
              <h3>1. Atomic number and atomic mass</h3>
              <p>
                Elements are ordered by <strong>atomic number</strong> \(Z\),
                the number of protons in the nucleus. In general, atomic mass
                increases with atomic number, but there are small irregularities
                due to nuclear stability and isotopic composition.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Atomic radius</h3>
              <p>
                Atomic radius decreases across a period (left to right) as
                nuclear charge increases, pulling electrons closer, and
                increases down a group as new electron shells are added.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Electronegativity</h3>
              <p>
                Electronegativity measures how strongly an atom attracts
                electrons in a bond. On the Pauling scale:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  It <strong>increases</strong> across a period (toward the
                  right).
                </li>
                <li>It <strong>decreases</strong> down a group.</li>
                <li>Fluorine is the most electronegative element.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Metallic vs. nonmetallic character</h3>
              <p>
                Metallic character (tendency to lose electrons and form cations)
                increases down a group and toward the left of the table.
                Nonmetals dominate the upper right, including the halogens and
                noble gases.
              </p>

              <h2>Element categories used in this table</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Alkali metals:</strong> group 1 (except hydrogen),
                  very reactive, form +1 cations.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Alkaline earth metals:</strong> group 2, reactive
                  metals forming +2 cations.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Transition metals:</strong> d-block elements, often
                  form colored compounds and multiple oxidation states.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Post-transition metals & metalloids:</strong>
                  intermediate properties between metals and nonmetals.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Nonmetals:</strong> include hydrogen, carbon,
                  nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, sulfur, and selenium.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Halogens:</strong> group 17, highly reactive nonmetals
                  that form −1 anions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Noble gases:</strong> group 18, very low reactivity,
                  monatomic gases.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Lanthanides & actinides:</strong> f-block elements
                  with similar chemistry within each series.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Data sources and accuracy</h2>
              <p>
                Values in this periodic table are based on widely accepted
                reference data (IUPAC standard atomic weights and common
                literature values for physical properties). For teaching,
                problem‑solving, and everyday reference, these rounded values
                are more than sufficient. For high‑precision research, always
                consult the latest primary data tables.
              </p>
